\newlabel{fig:clipping}{{4}{15}{Training dynamics of Qwen3-1.7B-Base with GRPO and GRPO-DBB under clipping ranges $(0.2,0.28)$ and $(0.98,0.98)$. From left to right: (a) validation Acc@8, (b) policy-gradient clip fraction, (c) gradient norm, and (d) policy-gradient loss. GRPO-DBB suffers excessive clipping under the standard range; once the range is widened, it recovers strong performance. GRPO under the wider range shows no improvement, confirming that the gains of GRPO-DBB are due to the DBB estimator rather than the clip range}{figure.caption.11}{}}
\newlabel{fig:clipping@cref}{{[figure][4][]4}{[1][15][]15}{}{}{}}
\newlabel{ap:prior_sensitivity}{{E}{15}{Impact Statements}{section.E}{}}
\newlabel{ap:prior_sensitivity@cref}{{[section][5][]E}{[1][15][]15}{}{}{}}
\newlabel{fig:prior_sensitivity}{{5}{16}{(a) Heatmap of $\min _\lambda \mathrm {MSE}$ of the DBB estimator over $(\alpha _0,\beta _0)$. (b) MSE versus $\lambda $ for selected priors. The default symmetric prior $(\alpha _0,\beta _0)=(1,1)$ is competitive with the best prior and robust over a wide range of $\lambda $}{figure.caption.12}{}}
\newlabel{fig:prior_sensitivity@cref}{{[figure][5][]5}{[1][15][]16}{}{}{}}
